No.  There is no official scheduling mechanism for these.  See 1(a).<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;| Sub-Dumb Question 1(a): Are those types of encounters<br>
&gt;| FFA at the moment? <br>
<br>
<br>
No.  They are not FFA.  They are FCFS but there is a matter of convention that most of us (the groups that can &quot;do&quot; the event) abide by in determining who is there &quot;first&quot;.  Being there &quot;first&quot; is different for each of those encounters.  For instance, &quot;first&quot; for Nagafen was agreed upon by BotS, KEG, CIW, and a few others long before the Level-53-Nerf to be the first group that assembled in SolB and *successfully* pull the first set of Fire Giants out front and kill them.  Once the group did that, everyone else would leave.  For Vox, it was similar.  The first group to pull the Ice Giants successfully was there &quot;first&quot;.  Most all the Kunark big mobs also have similar &quot;first&quot; agreements that are group-to-group agreements among the guilds that kill them.  There has always been and continues to be quite a bit of organizational chat between most, if not all, of the larger groups on The Rathe that goes on outside of the scope and view of the calendar system.  When there are fewer than 3 to 5 groups doing something, it is easier to work it out in a sideband than to deal with calendar systems.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;| Sub-Dumb Question 1(b): If so, didn't scheduling of<br>
&gt;| Vox and Nagafen used to be on some sort of coordinated<br>
&gt;| system (or is this my imagination running away with me)? <br>
<br>
<br>
No, it never was.  Early on people would sometimes post on their guild forums and on the other guilds' forums who could also &quot;do&quot; those things but it was never really formalized.  Sometimes groups would reply to those posts saying that they wanted to do them too and would require a race to the mob.  It very quickly changed to the systems described in 1(a) because of the numbers of groups/people wanting to do them.  Unlike the planes, way back in the day there weren't 40+ groups that were capable of doing those things.  There were closer to 5 groups.  Today, I don't know how Vox/Nagafen are handled because of the Level-53-Nerf.  My guild doesn't deal with those two mobs anymore.  I think Vox is almost always available.  I haven't been paying attention but I don't think Vox has been killed more than a half dozen times on our server since the Level-53-Nerf.<br>
<br>
<br>
&gt;| Sub-Dumb Question 1(c): If they were, what led to<br>
&gt;| the change?<br>
<br>
<br>
Too many people were wanting to do those things.  More people means harder to coordinate.  After you had to start posting on 123212 different guild boards that you wanted to do a dragon it simply was too much overhead.  FCFS is far easier to judge when there are only a handful of groups that attempt the mob.<br>
<br>
From what I have observed on our server (and probably occurrs on others where there are more than one guild that does it all) is that there are several stages in event planning.  At first, there is one group that can do the mob.  No coordination necessary.  At some point, a second group &quot;beats&quot; the first group to set up and gets a shot or a few and eventually succeeds.  As the second group gets more proficient, these first two groups usually make some sort of arrangement of sharing or define what FCFS rules there will be.  After a while, a third and a fourth group start attempting and eventually succeed.  At this point, more communication is required to modify the (then) current rules to include provisions for all the groups involved.  As the number of groups grows past 5 or so, more formalized rules have to be applied.  As the number gets probably to more than  7, some sort of global communication scheme has to come about (like a calendar system) where the current agreed upon rules are posted publicly and others are invited to participate within those rules.  Eventually, when there get to be more than 12 or so groups, things start to break down.  Planes are easy, they are there every day.  Long spawn time mobs are a pain to deal with.  With 10 groups on Trakanon for instance, a simple round-robin scheme would mean that a single group gets a shot once each month.  For VS, that would be once every 2.5 months for the same 10 groups (not including Karnor's zone crashes).  When the number of groups for even every day spawn things reaches 20, a lot of friction starts to develop.  When the number reaches 30+, usually a revamp will has to occur or there will be mass tension and bad things start to happen.<br>
<br>
